docs.abstract: A professor thought he had created a class that could explore society’s fissures through a single sport. Then the pandemic struck, and basketball became more relevant than ever.
docs.snippet: A professor thought he had created a class that could explore society’s fissures through a single sport. Then the pandemic struck, and basketball became more relevant than ever.
docs.lead_paragraph: Shortly after New York University honored David Hollander, an assistant dean, with the college’s highest faculty honor in March 2019, he turned his attention on fine-tuning the syllabus for a new class that he had wanted to teach for 15 years.

headline.main: At N.Y.U., Explaining an Unraveling World Through Basketball
headline.print_headline: Lamenting a World in Turmoil, a Scholar Thinks One Sport Can Save It

docs.abstract: Lurid fantasies about urban hellscapes are all he has left.

docs.lead_paragraph: On Thursday morning I walked across much of Manhattan and back again. (Why are all the doctors’ offices on the East Side?) It was a beautiful day, and the city looked cheerful: Shops were open, people were drinking coffee in the sidewalk seating areas that have proliferated during the pandemic, Central Park was full of joggers and cyclists.

docs.abstract: A committee finished its search for a flag to replace the one with a Confederate emblem that had flown for 126 years. It now moves to a statewide ballot.
docs.snippet: A committee finished its search for a flag to replace the one with a Confederate emblem that had flown for 126 years. It now moves to a statewide ballot.
docs.lead_paragraph: The law setting forth the process to pick a new Mississippi flag had two main stipulations: The words “In God we trust” had to be on it, and the Confederate battle emblem, which had been featured prominently on the old one, could not.

headline.main: Mississippi Wants Magnolia to Be Centerpiece of New State Flag
headline.print_headline: Magnolia Flag Design Is in Hands of Mississippi Voters

docs.abstract: The city recorded 242 shootings in August, up from 91 last year, continuing a summer spike in gun violence that has become an issue in the presidential race.
docs.snippet: The city recorded 242 shootings in August, up from 91 last year, continuing a summer spike in gun violence that has become an issue in the presidential race.
docs.lead_paragraph: The steep rise in gun violence that has rattled New York City and intensified the debate over policing continued at an alarming rate in August, as shootings more than doubled over the same period last year and murders rose by nearly 50 percent, the police said.

headline.main: A Violent August in N.Y.C.: Shootings Double, and Murder Is Up by 50%
headline.print_headline: Finger-Pointing Continues as New York Sees Another Month of Violent Crime

docs.abstract: Presenting himself as a warrior against identity politics, the president has increasingly made appeals to the grievances of white supporters a centerpiece of his re-election campaign.
docs.snippet: Presenting himself as a warrior against identity politics, the president has increasingly made appeals to the grievances of white supporters a centerpiece of his re-election campaign.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After a summer when hundreds of thousands of people took to the streets protesting racial injustice against Black Americans, President Trump has made it clear over the last few days that, in his view, the country’s real race problem is bias against white Americans.

headline.main: More Than Ever, Trump Casts Himself as the Defender of White America
headline.print_headline: Trump Makes White Grievance a Pillar of His Campaign
